## [1] "Inherited retinal disorders (IRD) have become a primary focus of gene therapy research since the success of AAV-based therapeutics (voretigene neparvovec-rzyl) for Leber congenital amaurosis type 2 (LCA2). Dozens of monogenic IRDs could be potentially treated with a similar approach using adeno-associated virus (AAV) to transfer a functional gene into the retina. Here, we present the results of design, production and in vitro testing of the AAV serotype 9 (AAV9) vector carrying the codon-optimized (co) copy of aryl hydrocarbon receptor interacting protein like-1 (AIPL1) as a possible treatment for LCA4. The pAAV-AIPL1co was able to successfully transduce retinal pigment epithelium cells (ARPE-19) and initiate expression of human AIPL1. Intriguingly, cells transduced with AAV9-AIPL1co showed much less antiviral response than AAV9-AIPL1wt (wild type AIPL1 ) transduced. RNA-sequencing (RNA-seq) analysis of trans-differentiated ARPE-19 cells transduced with AAV9-AIPL1co demonstrated the significant differences in expression of genes involved in innate immune response. In contrast, AAV9-AIPL1wt induced prominent activation of multiple interferon-stimulated genes. The key part of possible regulatory molecular mechanism is activation of dsRNA-responsive antiviral oligoadenylate synthetases, and significant increase in level of histone coding genes’ transcripts overrepresented in RNA-seq data (i.e. H1, H2A, H2B, H3 and H4). The RNA-seq data suggests that AAV9-AIPL1co exhibiting less immunogenicity than AAV9-AIPL1wt can be used for potency testing using relevant animal models to develop future therapeutics for LCA4."

Loading and Filtering Data

I began this step in A1 by using the getGEOSuppFiles() code as found in lecture (Isserlin 2024a). I collected the supplementary files because that is where the data was for my paper; I was able to find the relevant file, and luckily in my case there was only 1 data file to choose from.

#load GEOquery
library(GEOquery)

#obtain supplmentary files from GEO (specifically the one .tar file, in this case)
gsupp <- getGEOSuppFiles(geoid, fetch_files = FALSE)
gfilename <- gsupp$fname[2]

#set download directory 
download_dir <- "~/"

gfile = getGEOSuppFiles(geoid, baseDir = download_dir, fetch_files = TRUE)

For this chunk and the next few chunks, I worked on filtering my data. First, I needed to filter it by separating the numeric and non-numeric columns (Bhalla, n.d.b). I was very lucky with my data where the HGNC codes were already mapped to each gene, however that did mean I subsequently had two columns of non-numeric data which none of my codes were happy with at all. I kept running into errors until I did the following.

After extracting the non-numeric data, I noticed I had many rows where all values were 0. Meaning there were some genes were in the control they were 0, and also under any treatment. I used the following code to remove them, and then applied the same code to remove very, very low values (Bhalla, n.d.a). This is where I removed any rows where ALL values were less than 5 in each row. However, if even one column had a value above 5, I kept that row.

#filter data from very values with '0' in all columns
row_sums <- rowSums(geodata[, -c(1, 2)])
geodata_filtered <- geodata[row_sums != 0, ]

After filtering that way, I needed to do futher filtering by removing any rows where there was ‘NA’ (Bhalla, n.d.a). I removed these rows to finally be left with my final filtered dataset ready to go through normalization.

#filter out NA data (data where columns have NA)
geodata_numeric_no_na <- na.omit(geodata_numeric)

#conduct filtering again for both 0 and <5 (same as above, however re-doing)
row_sums1 <- rowSums(geodata_numeric_no_na[, -c(1, 2)])
geodata_numeric_no_na_0 <- geodata_numeric_no_na[row_sums != 0, ]

row_min1 <- apply(geodata_numeric_no_na[, -c(1, 2)], 1, min, na.rm = TRUE)
geodata_numeric_no_na_1 <- geodata_numeric_no_na[row_min >= 5, ]

#combine the two filtered data frames in one
g_n_nona_comb <- rbind(geodata_numeric_no_na_0, geodata_numeric_no_na_1)

#left with final, filtered dataset pre-normalization

Normalization

In this part, I needed to add back in the geneIDs (or gene names, however I was only able to choose one column thus chose one more easily identifiable). This was because when going through normalization, I needed the genes as labels. I added them back in as row names, instead of a column on their own.

#get the geneIDs from original filtered and combine, then omit any NA values 
geodata_names <- rbind(geodata_filtered, geodata_filtered_1)
omit_geodata_names <- na.omit(geodata_names)

#extract row names and set them to the filtered dataset 
gene_names <- omit_geodata_names$geneID
dif_row_names <- make.unique(gene_names, sep = "_")
rownames(filtered_g_n_nona_comb) <- dif_row_names

#obtain final dataset with row names/geneIDs
head(filtered_g_n_nona_comb)

Here is where I conducted normalization using edgeR, with guidance from the lectures in this course (Isserlin 2024c, 2024b).

#load edgeR library
library(edgeR)
## Loading required package: limma
## 
## Attaching package: 'limma'
## The following object is masked from 'package:BiocGenerics':
## 
##     plotMA
#define column names from the filtered dataset (as the column names are the condition names)
colnames <- colnames(filtered_g_n_nona_comb)

#change to matrix to use with edgeR
matrixg <- as.matrix(filtered_g_n_nona_comb)

#calculate normalization
d = DGEList(counts = matrixg, group = colnames)
d = calcNormFactors(d)

norm_edgeR <- cpm(d)

I plotted my MDS using limma, to show what normalization did for my data (Isserlin 2024a, 2024c, 2024d).

#load limma
library(limma)

#plot MDS plot 
limma::plotMDS(d, labels = NULL, pch = 1, col = c("darkgreen", "blue", "orange", "darkblue", "pink", "red", "purple", "grey", "black", "brown", "green", "lightblue") [factor(colnames)])

#define legend and other plot dimensions
legend("bottomright", legend=levels(factor(colnames)), pch=c(1), col= c("darkgreen", "blue", "orange", "darkblue", "pink", "red", "purple", "grey", "black", "brown", "green", "lightblue"), title="Class", bty = 'n', cex = 0.5)

Before moving onto Assignment 2, I also constructed boxplots using ggplot2. These boxplots are shown to represent the difference between the original dataset, the filtered dataset, and then finally the normalized dataset (Isserlin 2024a; “Create elegant data visualisations using the grammar of graphics,” n.d.).

#load ggplot2
library(ggplot2)

#define numeric data again
geodata_numeric <- geodata[, sapply(geodata, is.numeric)]
gplot_numeric <- log2(geodata_numeric)
gplot <- cbind(geodata[, !sapply(geodata, is.numeric)], gplot_numeric)

#plot original data BEFORE filtering
plot.new()
boxplot(geodata_numeric, xlab = "Samples", ylab = "Values", las = 2, cex = 0.5, cex.lab = 0.5, cex.axis = 0.5, main = "RNASeqSamples")
abline(h = median(apply(gplot_numeric, 2, median)), col = "green", lwd = 0.6, lty = "dashed")

Assignment 2: Differential Gene Expression and MA + Volcano Plot

To begin this part of the assignment, I needed to define my column data as my code was not working unless I included this part. I was able to use the DESeq2 package and the R errors to help me figure out what was going on (Love, Anders, and Huber 2024).

#define column names to use in DESeq2 as it was not running code without this 
sample_names <- colnames(filtered_g_n_nona_comb)

#use colData to define the column names of data frame

rownames(colData) <- sample_names

After this, I loaded the DESeq2 library and ran DESeq2 (Love, Anders, and Huber 2024). I used DESeq2 for the majority of this assignment because DESeq2 is able to both normalize and differentiate findings. This is especially useful as it provided for me the base mean, log2FoldChange, as well as standard p-values and the adjusted p-values, of which the latter are vital to the rest of the calculations. I also chose DESeq2, compared to continuing with edgeR, because my data includes many repetitions of the same condition. I defined these repetitions as my model design, as seen below, so that my data is accurately represented (“Error:The design matrix has the same number of samples and coefficients to fit, so estimation of dispersion is not possible. Treating samples as replicates was deprecated in v1.20 and no longer su,” n.d.; “Design model for DESeq2 analysis,” n.d.). I printed the results both as a DESeq2 object, and as a data frame to display the findings. I also included a summary of my results, to allow for easier comprehension.

After I got my results, I filtered them further to get the significant genes, by setting thresholds for my adjusted p-values and my log2FoldChange (Love, Anders, and Huber 2024). I set thresholds for these as DESeq2 uses the Benjamini-Hochberg (BH) method to correct p-values and control the false discovery rate (FDR). (Pipis and Pipis 2023).

#using the native DESeq2 subset function, define parameters to obtain significant genes
resSig <- subset(results, padj < 0.05 & log2FoldChange > 0.6)

Question Answers Part 1

1. Calculate p-values for each of the genes in your expression set. How many genes were significantly differentially expressed? What thresholds did you use and why?

A: There were many genes that were differential expressed; by setting thresholds of p < 0.05, and l2fc > 0.6, I was able to get 416 genes that were significantly expressed. I used these thresholds because due to the large amount of genes, I was able to control for a very low p-value. By setting the log2FoldChange threshold, I was able to receive the significantly differentially expressed genes, as l2fc calcualtes this (“FPKM Files,” n.d.).

2. Multiple hypothesis testing - correct your p-values using a multiple hypothesis correction method. Which method did you use? And Why? How many genes passed correction?

A: As apart of DESeq2, p-values are already corrected (and can be found under the adjusted p-values (padj)). The method DESeq2 uses to correct the p-values is the Benjamini-Hochberg (BH) which corrects using the false discovery rate (FDR). (“DESEQ2,” n.d.; Pipis and Pipis 2023)

Heatmap

I then coded for a heatmap to further represent my data, using my DESeq2 object. (“pheatmap function - RDocumentation,” n.d.)

#load pheatmap
library(pheatmap)

#define 'select' data from DESeq2 object 
select <- order(rowMeans(counts(gdds,normalized=TRUE)),
                decreasing=TRUE)[1:20]
#define column data
col_d <- colData(gdds)

#create data frame for annotation
df <- data.frame(condition = col_d$condition, sizeFactor = col_d$sizeFactor)

#create heatmap
heatmap <- pheatmap(assay(gdds)[select,], cluster_rows=FALSE, show_rownames=FALSE, cluster_cols=FALSE, annotation_col=df,
         main = "Heatmap",
         xlabel = "Treatments")
